[1] Canada - Saskatchewan
Date: 29 Jun 2011
Source: CTV Saskatoon [edited]
http://saskatoon.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110629/sas-anthrax-110629/20110629/?hub=Saskatoon


Livestock producers should be cautious of anthrax this year
-----------------------------------------------------------
The naturally occurring illness can cause staggering, convulsions,
and rapid death in animals. Unfortunately, the wet weather this year
is increasing the risk of disease. A University of Saskatchewan
veterinary professor is reminding livestock producers to protect their
herds against anthrax.

Flooded land could be a problem for more than just raising crops, it
could also mean a deadly season for livestock producers. Dr Chris
Clark of the Western College of Veterinary Medicine says that the
first predictor for the potential of anthrax is a wet spring. Despite
a few isolated cases since, the last outbreak occurred in the summer
of 2006. And so to avoid the necessary widespread destruction of
animals, Dr Clark says cattle, horses, bison, and other grazing
animals should be vaccinated.

"I think the producers in areas where there has been anthrax in the
past, if they've been vaccinating in the past, this is a year to make
sure you vaccinate and be ultra-cautious of it," says Clark. Clark
says the soggy conditions have created ideal conditions for anthrax
spores to surface. "The bacterial spores live deep in the soil, and
they'll float. So, if you flood, you wash them out of the deep soil
and bring them to the surface." Clark explains the floating spores are
not a high risk because they are spread out on the water. However, he
says the threat becomes greater when the flooded land starts to dry
up. The large puddles recede to become small puddles with lush grass
around them -- concentrating the spores and creating a disease risk.
"So, at the moment, if it dries up rapidly, this could be a year for
anthrax," says Clark.

According to the Canadian Veterinary Journal, during the 2006
outbreak the Canadian Food Inspection Agency recorded a total of 804
livestock deaths from anthrax.

--
communicated by
ProMED-Mail correspondent Susan Baekeland

